#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1943
#, no-c-format
msgid "Best practices for changing <literal>sysctl</literal> settings"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1944
#, no-c-format
msgid "Optimal sysctl settings can vary greatly depending on the specific use case, hardware and workload of your system. It is recommended to test changes thoroughly and monitor system performance after applying new sysctl configurations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1953
#, no-c-format
msgid "sysfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1955
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in accepts any valid file path under the system file system, or the <filename>/sys/</filename> directory. The plug-in checks whether a file path is valid and can read and write the values in the files that are part of the configuration. For example, consider the following configuration of the <literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1963
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sysfs</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1964
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[sysfs]\n"
      "/sys/bus/workqueue/devices/writeback/cpumask = 2,6 <co xml:id=\"non-isolated-cpu-mask-value\"/>\n"
      "/sys/devices/virtual/workqueue/cpumask = 3-5 <co xml:id=\"non-isolated-cpu-mask-range\"/>\n"
      "/sys/devices/system/machinecheck/machinecheck*/ignore_ce = 1 <co xml:id=\"ignore-ce\"/>\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1973
#, no-c-format
msgid "Single CPUs separated by comma. Only those CPUs that are not isolated using the <parameter>isolcpus</parameter> kernel boot parameter are allowed. To check the CPUs that are already isolated, run the <command>grep isolcpus /proc/cmdline</command> command. To check the total number of CPUs in your system, run the <command>lscpu | grep \"^CPU(s):\"</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1982
#, no-c-format
msgid "Range of CPUs. Only those CPUs that are not isolated using the <parameter>isolcpus</parameter> kernel boot parameter are allowed. To check the CPUs that are already isolated, run the command <command>grep isolcpus /proc/cmdline</command> . To check the total number of CPUs in your system, run the <command>lscpu | grep \"^CPU(s):\"</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:1991
#, no-c-format
msgid "Corrected Errors (CEs) are hardware errors that the system has detected and corrected automatically. The <literal>ignore_ce</literal> attribute is a sysfs setting that controls whether the system must report these corrected errors. When <literal>ignore_ce</literal> is set to <literal>1</literal> , the system ignores corrected errors, meaning they are not logged or reported to the operating system's error handling mechanisms. When <literal>ignore_ce</literal> is set to <literal>0</literal> (the default value), corrected errors are reported and logged by the system, allowing administrators to monitor them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2006
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2008
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>systemd</literal> plug-in focuses on configuring the parameters of &systemd;, which is the system and service manager for &sles;. For example, consider the plug-in configuration for CPU affinity of &systemd; processes:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2014
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>systemd</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2015
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[systemd]\n"
      "cpu_affinity=0,1,2 <co xml:id=\"systemd-plugin-cpu-affinity\"/>\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2021
#, no-c-format
msgid "Binds the systemd services to multiple specified CPU cores. By default, it is <literal>None</literal> . In this example, the services are configured to run on CPU cores <literal>0</literal> , <literal>1</literal> and <literal>2</literal> . Alternate ways of passing the values include passing a range of CPU cores, such as <literal>0-2</literal> . However, you <emphasis>cannot</emphasis> pass on as values the CPU cores that you have declared as <parameter>isolated_cores</parameter> in the file <filename>/etc/tuned/cpu-partitioning-variables.conf</filename> . Configuring the <parameter>cpu_affinity</parameter> parameter in the plug-in is equivalent to configuring the <parameter>CPUAffinity</parameter> in the &systemd; configuration file <filename>/etc/systemd/system.conf</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2040
#, no-c-format
msgid "script"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2042
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>script</literal> plug-in allows users to execute custom scripts that &tunedapp; runs at different stages. System administrators can use it to automate several system configurations and optimizations by specifying paths to such scripts. Common parameters and their possible values include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2050
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>priority</parameter> : An integer value that sets the priority level for the script. &tunedapp; executes scripts based on their priority, with lower numbers indicating higher priority. So, a priority of <literal>5</literal> means this script has a low priority compared to scripts with a priority number lower than <literal>5</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2059
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>script</parameter> : This specifies the path to the script that &tunedapp; executes. You can either provide the absolute path to the script as its value, or use the <varname>PROFILE_DIR</varname> variable to pass the relative path to the script."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2067
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, consider the following use of a relative script path:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2071
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using variables for including a relative script path in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2072
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[script]\n"
      "priority=5\n"
      "script=${i:PROFILE_DIR}/script.sh\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2079
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resource for definition of variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2080
#, no-c-format
msgid "For a list of useful variables, inspect the constants defined in the source file <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/redhat-performance/tuned/blob/&tunedver;/tuned/consts.py\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2088
#, no-c-format
msgid "scheduler"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2090
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in is used to manage the isolation of CPU cores and the selection of processes for management based on adding to an approved list or a blocklist. This plug-in is primarily concerned with isolating specific CPU cores and managing which processes should or should not be managed by the scheduler. Commonly used parameters and their possible values include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2099
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>isolated_cores</parameter> : Isolates specific CPU cores from the general scheduler. Processes can be pinned to these isolated cores to ensure they run without interference from other system processes. To pass values to this parameter, use comma-separated integers representing the cores, or the bitmask of the integers in the hexadecimal format. For example, <literal>isolated_cores=0,1</literal> can also be represented by <literal>0x3</literal> in a more compact manner."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2110
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>ps_whitelist</parameter> : A list of allowed process names that the scheduler plug-in is empowered to manage. Only processes matching this pattern are considered for scheduling adjustments. Pass regular expressions of process names as values to this parameter. For example, <literal>.*</literal> matches all processes, and <literal>^bash$</literal> matches only the <literal>bash</literal> process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2120
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>ps_blacklist</parameter> : A list of process names that the plug-in excludes from management. Processes matching this pattern are not adjusted by the plug-in. Pass regular expressions of process names as values to this parameter. For example, <literal>.*</literal> matches all processes, and <literal>^idle$</literal> matches only the <literal>idle</literal> process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2129
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, consider the following configuration for the <literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2134
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>scheduler</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2135
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "isolated_cores=0x3\n"
      "ps_whitelist=.*\n"
      "ps_blacklist=^idle$;.*pmd.*;.*PMD.*;^DPDK;.*qemu-kvm.*\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2144
#, no-c-format
msgid "bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2146
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in is used to apply performance profiles that require changes to the boot parameters of the system. These changes are made in the boot loader configuration file (typically &grub; configuration) and are applied when the system boots up. This plug-in is particularly useful for optimizing system performance by setting specific kernel parameters, such as those controlling CPU isolation or power management, as well as other boot-time settings that can affect the overall system behavior and performance."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2155
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common parameters and their values are summarized below:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2160
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>grub2_cfg_file</parameter> : Specifies the &grub; configuration file to modify. If not provided, the plug-in uses the default GRUB2 configuration files located in the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2167
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>initrd_dst_img</parameter> : Sets the destination path for the initrd image. If specified, the initrd image is copied to this location. The path must be absolute, and if it is not provided, the default boot directory is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2174
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>initrd_add_img</parameter> : Adds the path to an initrd image in the &grub; configuration, so that custom initrd images can be used during the boot process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2181
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>initrd_add_dir</parameter> : Adds a directory to be included in the initrd image. This parameter specifies the path to a directory whose contents are packaged into an initrd image and included in the boot configuration. This is useful for adding custom modules or scripts to the initrd."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2189
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>initrd_remove_dir</parameter> : A boolean option to specify whether to remove the directory specified in <parameter>initrd_add_dir</parameter> after it has been packaged into the initrd image. If set to <literal>True</literal> , the source directory is deleted after the initrd image is created."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2197
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>cmdline</parameter> : Specifies additional kernel command-line parameters to be added to the &grub; configuration. This allows the addition of custom kernel parameters that can optimize system performance or behavior based on the specific needs of the workload."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2205
#, no-c-format
msgid "As an example, consider the following configuration for the <literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2210
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>bootloader</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2211
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[bootloader]\n"
      "cmdline=\"isolcpus=1-3 nohz_full=1-3 intel_pstate=disable\"\n"
      "initrd_add_img=\"/path/to/custom-initrd.img\"\n"
      "initrd_add_dir=\"/path/to/custom-initrd-dir\"\n"
      "initrd_remove_dir=True\n"
      "initrd_dst_img=\"/boot/initrd-custom.img\"\n"
      "grub2_cfg_file=\"/etc/grub2.cfg\"\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2224
#, no-c-format
msgid "net"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2226
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>net</literal> plug-in is used to configure several parameters for optimizing network performance. Common parameters and their values used with this plug-in are summarized below:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2233
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>devices</parameter> : Specifies a comma-separated list of the network device names. For example, <literal>devices=eth0,eth1</literal> . By default, the settings are applied on all network devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2240
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>dynamic</parameter> : Boolean values ( <literal>true</literal> / <literal>false</literal> ) that enable or disable dynamic tuning based on network load."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2247
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>wake_on_lan</parameter> : Configures Wake-on-LAN (WoL) settings using any combination of the following characters:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2253
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>p</literal> : Wake on PHY activity."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2258
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>u</literal> : Wake on unicast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2263
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>m</literal> : Wake on multicast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2268
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>b</literal> : Wake on broadcast messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2273
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>a</literal> : Wake on ARP."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2278
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>g</literal> : Wake on MagicPacket <superscript>TM</superscript> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2283
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>s</literal> : Enable SecureOn <superscript>TM</superscript> for MagicPacket <superscript>TM</superscript> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2289
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>d</literal> : Disable WoL."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2296
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>nf_conntrack_hashsize</parameter> : Integer value setting the size of the connection-tracking hash table."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2302
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>features</parameter> : A dictionary of network device feature names and their desired states. For example, <literal>tx-checksum: off, sg: on</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2308
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>coalesce</parameter> : A dictionary of packet coalescing parameters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2313
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>adaptive-rx</literal> and <literal>adaptive-tx</literal> have the possible values <literal>on</literal> or <literal>off</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2319
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following ones have integer values: <literal>rx-usecs</literal> , <literal>rx-frames</literal> , <literal>rx-usecs-irq</literal> , <literal>rx-frames-irq</literal> , <literal>tx-usecs</literal> , <literal>tx-frames</literal> , <literal>tx-usecs-irq</literal> , <literal>tx-frames-irq</literal> , <literal>stats-block-usecs</literal> , <literal>pkt-rate-low</literal> , <literal>rx-usecs-low</literal> , <literal>rx-frames-low</literal> , <literal>tx-usecs-low</literal> , <literal>tx-frames-low</literal> , <literal>pkt-rate-high</literal> , <literal>rx-usecs-high</literal> , <literal>rx-frames-high</literal> , <literal>tx-usecs-high</literal> , <literal>tx-frames-high</literal> , <literal>sample-interval</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2336
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>pause</parameter> : A dictionary of pause frame parameters. The following pause frame parameters have <literal>on</literal> or <literal>off</literal> values: <literal>autoneg</literal> , <literal>rx</literal> and <literal>tx</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2344
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>ring</parameter> : A dictionary of ring buffer sizes. Each of the following ring buffer size parameters has integer values: <literal>rx</literal> , <literal>rx-mini</literal> , <literal>rx-jumbo</literal> and <literal>tx</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2352
#, no-c-format
msgid "As an example of configuring network device parameters, consider the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2356
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>net</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2357
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[net]\n"
      "devices=eth0,eth1\n"
      "dynamic=true\n"
      "wake_on_lan=g\n"
      "nf_conntrack_hashsize=16384\n"
      "features=tx-checksum:off, sg:on\n"
      "coalesce=adaptive-rx:on, rx-usecs:50, rx-frames:32\n"
      "pause=autoneg:on, rx:on, tx:off\n"
      "ring=rx:2048, tx:1024\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2372
#, no-c-format
msgid "vm"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2374
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>vm</literal> plug-in optimizes memory management in virtualized environments. It provides mechanisms for tuning memory-related parameters, specifically focusing on the management of Transparent HugePages (THP). Commonly used parameters and their values for this plug-in include the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2382
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>transparent_hugepage</parameter> or <parameter>transparent_hugepages</parameter> : Often used interchangeably, these parameters are aliases for each other and perform the function of controlling the behavior of Transparent HugePages. The common properties and values associated with this parameter are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2391
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>enabled</literal> : Controls the overall enabling of transparent huge pages. Possible values are <literal>always</literal> , <literal>madvise</literal> and <literal>never</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2398
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>defrag</literal> : Determines when, if defragmentation should occur. Possible values are <literal>always</literal> , <literal>defer</literal> , <literal>madvise</literal> , <literal>defer+madvise</literal> and <literal>never</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2406
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>khugepaged</literal> : Configures settings related to the khugepaged daemon, including options such as <literal>scan_sleep_millisecs</literal> and <literal>alloc_sleep_millisecs</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2415
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, consider the following configuration of the <literal>vm</literal> plug-in in a &tunedapp; profile:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2420
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>vm</literal> plug-in configuration in a &tunedapp; profile"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2421
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[vm]\n"
      "transparent_hugepages.enabled=always\n"
      "transparent_hugepage.defrag=always\n"
      "transparent_hugepages.khugepaged.scan_sleep_millisecs=10000\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2431
#, no-c-format
msgid "eeepc_she"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2433
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>eeepc_she</literal> plug-in enhances power management on ASUS EeePC netbooks, specifically those equipped with the Super Hybrid Engine (SHE) technology. It optimizes system performance by dynamically adjusting CPU frequencies and power states to achieve a balance between energy efficiency and processing power. The commonly used parameters and their values are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2442
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>load_threshold_normal</parameter> : Threshold for load to switch to normal mode. Default value is <literal>0.6</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2448
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>load_threshold_powersave</parameter> : Threshold for load to switch to powersave mode. Default value is <literal>0.4</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2454
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>she_powersave</parameter> : Value to set SHE to power-saving mode. Default value is <literal>2</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2460
#, no-c-format
msgid "<parameter>she_normal</parameter> : Value to set SHE to normal mode. Default value is <literal>1</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2472
#, no-c-format
msgid "More information"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2474
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information, refer to the following resources:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2480
#, no-c-format
msgid "The official Web site of the &tunedapp; project: <link xlink:href=\"https://tuned-project.org/\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2486
#, no-c-format
msgid "Source code repository on GitHub: <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/redhat-performance/tuned\"/> . You may find the following resources to be particularly helpful:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2493
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuration files for several profiles are available at <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/redhat-performance/tuned/tree/&tunedver;/profiles\"/> . These configuration examples can provide a good starting point for creating a custom profile that is not available as part of the <package>tuned</package> package for &sles;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2502
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are interested in implementing the plug-ins that monitor and dynamically tune the system based on values provided in the profiles, the source code is available at <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/redhat-performance/tuned/tree/&tunedver;/tuned/plugins\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2513
#, no-c-format
msgid "Refer to appropriate version of &tunedapp; source code"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_tuned.xml:2514
#, no-c-format
msgid "Check for the version of &tuned; in your &sles; system by running the <command>tuned --version</command> command. On the GitHub repository, select the corresponding branch or tag for inspecting the source code of the specific &tuned; version installed on your system."
msgstr ""

